1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,336
Eiko Araki is an expert of the Sanuki Kagari Temari, a Japanese traditional craft.

2
00:00:08,336 --> 00:00:15,879
The craft has been passed down for more than 1,000 years on the island of Shikoku.

3
00:00:15,879 --> 00:00:23,693
Araki is at the center of a small circle of women who are working hard to make “temari.”

4
00:00:23,693 --> 00:00:30,235
These balls are small artistic objects that have colorful designs.

5
00:00:30,235 --> 00:00:33,631
They can take weeks or months to finish.

6
00:00:33,631 --> 00:00:39,653
Some cost hundreds of dollars although others are less costly.

7
00:00:39,653 --> 00:00:42,548
The balls are not for sports.

8
00:00:42,548 --> 00:00:48,901
They are created as special objects, carrying prayers for health and goodness.

9
00:00:48,901 --> 00:00:53,635
They might be treasured like a painting in a Western home.

10
00:00:53,635 --> 00:01:02,724
“Out of nothing, something this beautiful is born, bringing joy,” said Araki about the temari.

11
00:01:02,724 --> 00:01:11,002
“I want it to be remembered there are beautiful things in this world that can only be made by hand.”

12
00:01:11,002 --> 00:01:15,944
The area where temari began was good for growing cotton.

13
00:01:15,944 --> 00:01:21,525
The round creations continue to be made out of that material.

14
00:01:21,525 --> 00:01:34,277
At Araki’s studio, which also serves as head office for temari’s preservation society, there are 140 colors of cotton thread.

15
00:01:34,277 --> 00:01:42,229
The women dye them by hand, using plants, flowers and other natural ingredients.

16
00:01:42,229 --> 00:01:51,023
Outside the studio, cotton thread, in different colors, hangs outside in the shade to dry.

17
00:01:51,023 --> 00:01:56,043
The lengthy process starts with making the basic ball.

18
00:01:56,043 --> 00:02:01,755
The careful work with thread called stitching is done on the ball.

19
00:02:01,755 --> 00:02:10,449
The outer covering of rice grains, called husks, are cooked and then dried and placed in a piece of cotton.

20
00:02:10,449 --> 00:02:19,279
Then the materials are wound with thread, over and over, until, almost magically, a ball appears.

21
00:02:19,279 --> 00:02:21,805
Then the stitching begins.

22
00:00:00,000 --> 00:02:30,726
The balls are surprisingly hard, so each stitch requires a careful, almost painful, push.

23
00:02:30,726 --> 00:02:38,004
These days, temari is getting new recognition among Japanese and foreigners as well.

24
00:02:38,004 --> 00:02:49,158
Caroline Kennedy, for example, took lessons in the ball-making when she was United States ambassador to Japan 10 years ago.

25
00:02:49,158 --> 00:02:57,514
Yoshie Nakamura promotes Japanese handcrafted art in her shop at Tokyo’s Haneda airport.

26
00:02:57,514 --> 00:03:04,654
Nakamura says she features temari there because of its complex designs.

27
00:03:04,654 --> 00:03:14,698
“Temari that might have been everyday in a faraway era is now being used for interior decoration,” she said.

28
00:03:14,698 --> 00:03:24,325
“I really feel each Sanuki Kagari Temari speaks of a special, one-and-only existence in the world.”

29
00:03:24,325 --> 00:03:31,922
Araki has come up with some newer designs that feel both modern and historical.

30
00:03:31,922 --> 00:03:37,056
She is trying to make the balls more available for everyday life.

31
00:03:37,056 --> 00:03:43,565
For example, some of the balls can be used to beautify Christmas trees.

32
00:03:43,565 --> 00:03:47,474
Araki often travels to Tokyo to teach.

33
00:03:47,474 --> 00:03:52,146
But mostly she works and gives lessons in her studio.

34
00:03:52,146 --> 00:03:55,960
She started out as a metalwork artist.

35
00:03:55,960 --> 00:04:05,706
Her husband’s parents were temari masters who worked hard to bring back the artform when it was at risk of dying out.

36
00:04:05,706 --> 00:04:08,454
They were not emotional people.

37
00:04:08,454 --> 00:04:15,401
They rarely gave praise and instead always scolded her, she remembers.

38
00:04:15,401 --> 00:04:26,336
It is a “tough love” teaching method that is common in many Japanese traditional arts, from Kabuki acting to hogaku music.

39
00:04:26,336 --> 00:04:32,033
These art forms demand a lifetime of selfless devotion.

40
00:04:32,033 --> 00:04:41,407
Today, only a small number of people, all women, can make the temari balls to traditional standards.

41
00:04:41,407 --> 00:04:47,619
Araki said that the most difficult issue is training the next generation.

42
00:04:47,619 --> 00:04:58,908
She added that it usually “takes over 10 years to train them, so you need people who are willing to continue the craft for a very long time."

43
00:04:58,908 --> 00:05:09,637
But, she explained, “When people start to feel joy along with the hardship that comes with making temari, they tend to keep going.”

44
00:05:09,637 --> 00:05:12,529
I’m John Russell.